StringWithMarkup.String: Tetramethylammonium chloride's production and use as a chemical intermediate, catalyst, and inhibitor may result in its release to the environment through various waste streams. Its use in hydrofracking fluid as a clay stabilizer will result in its direct release to the environment. If released to air, an estimated vapor pressure of 1.2X10-8 mm Hg at 25 °C indicates tetramethylammonium chloride will exist in both the vapor and particulate phases in the atmosphere. Vapor-phase tetramethylammonium chloride will be degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals; the half-life for this reaction in air is estimated to be 25 hours. Particulate-phase tetramethylammonium chloride will be removed from the atmosphere by wet or dry deposition. Tetramethylammonium chloride does not contain chromophores that absorb at wavelengths >290 nm, and therefore is not expected to be susceptible to direct photolysis by sunlight. If released to soil, tetramethylammonium chloride is expected to have very high mobility based upon an estimated Koc of 8. Tetramethylammonium chloride is a quaternary ammonium salt, indicating that this compound will exist in the cation form in the environment and cations generally adsorb more strongly to soils containing organic carbon and clay than their neutral counterparts. Volatilization from moist soil surfaces is not expected to be an important fate process based upon an estimated Henry's Law constant of 4.2X10-12 atm-cu m/mole. No biodegradation occurred using activated sludge in a respirometer test suggesting that biodegradation is not an important environmental fate process in soil or water; cation compounds are known to be toxic to microorganisms. If released into water, tetramethylammonium chloride is not expected to adsorb to suspended solids and sediment based upon the estimated Koc. Volatilization from water surfaces is not expected to be an important fate process based upon this compound's estimated Henry's Law constant. Tetramethylammonium chloride is a salt and exists in the cation form at pH values of 5 to 9; therefore volatilization from water surfaces is not expected to be an important fate process. An estimated BCF of 3 suggests the potential for bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is low. Hydrolysis is not expected to be an important environmental fate process since this compound is a quaternary ammonium salt. Occupational exposure to tetramethylammonium chloride may occur through inhalation and dermal contact with this compound at workplaces where tetramethylammonium chloride is produced or used. (SRC)

Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water.  Since adsorption occurs predominantly by partition into the soil organic matter, it is more useful to normalize the Kd value to the organic carbon content of a soil and express the distribution coefficient in Koc (organic carbon normalized distribution coefficient).  The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.

Reference.Description: The PATENTSCOPE database from WIPO includes patent and chemical structure search (with a free account) that gives access to millions of patent documents. The World Intellectual Property Organisation (WIPO) is a specialized United Nations (UN) agency headquartered in Geneva (Switzerland). Our mission is to lead the development of a balanced and effective international Intellectual Property (IP) system that enables innovation and creativity for the benefit of all. We help governments, businesses and society realize the benefits of Intellectual Property and are notably a world reference source for IP information.
